VoteHub

A modern web-based voting and discussion platform inspired by community-driven forums like Reddit. Users can create posts, vote on content, participate in discussions, and interact with other members through a secure and scalable platform.

Why I Built This

I wanted to challenge myself by building a full-stack
 application that combines real-world backend architecture with features commonly found in large social platforms. The goal wasn’t just to create another CRUD application, but to design a system that handles authentication, caching, voting logic, database relationships, and user interactions in a clean and efficient way.

Features

* User registration and authentication
* Secure login and session management
* Create, edit, and delete posts
* Upvote and downvote system
* Commenting and discussions
* Redis-powered caching for improved performance
* SQL database for persistent data storage
* User-specific permissions and authorization
* RESTful API architecture
* Input validation and error handling
* Responsive web interface

Tech Stack

Backend

* Python
* SQL Database
* Redis
* REST API Architecture
* Authentication & Authorization


Infrastructure

* Redis for caching and performance optimization
* Relational database for data integrity and scalability

Technical Challenges

One of the most interesting parts of this project was designing the voting system. Ensuring that users could only vote once while still allowing them to change or remove votes required careful database logic and state management.

Another challenge was integrating Redis effectively. Instead of simply storing data, I used caching strategies to reduce database load and improve response times for frequently accessed content.

Authentication and authorization also required special attention to ensure user data remained secure and protected from unauthorized actions.

